{"behaviors":[{"behavior_id":1,"description":"Migrations are applied in ascending numeric order determined by the filename prefix.","minimum_level":"Integration","justification":"MOCK-MISS: yes, a mocked file list or DB executor can hide real ordering bugs from filename parsing + discovery. REAL-INFRA: no subprocess/network requirement beyond local DB/filesystem. MOCK-HIDE: yes, mocking execution would not reveal wrong on-disk ordering behavior. LLM-DEP/MULTI-STEP: no.","test_description":"Create a temp migrations directory with out-of-order filenames (e.g., 001, 010, 002), run the real runner against a local Postgres test DB, and assert both execution side effects and _migrations rows reflect 001->002->010 order.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.25,"Integration":0.7,"System":0.05,"Agentic":0,"Workflow":0}},{"behavior_id":2,"description":"A migration that has already been applied is not re-executed on a subsequent run.","minimum_level":"Integration","justification":"MOCK-MISS: yes, idempotency depends on persisted DB metadata across runs. REAL-INFRA: no subprocess needed. MOCK-HIDE: yes, mocking _migrations checks can miss duplicate execution bugs. LLM-DEP/MULTI-STEP: no.","test_description":"Run the runner twice against the same local Postgres DB with a migration that inserts a sentinel row; verify row count remains 1 and _migrations contains one record for that migration.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.15,"Integration":0.8,"System":0.05,"Agentic":0,"Workflow":0}},{"behavior_id":3,"description":"When a migration statement fails, its changes are rolled back automatically and no further migrations in the same run are attempted.","minimum_level":"Integration","justification":"MOCK-MISS: yes, rollback correctness depends on real transaction behavior in Postgres. REAL-INFRA: local DB is enough; no subprocess required. MOCK-HIDE: yes, mocked transaction APIs may always